                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Iraq isn't allowed to have nukes primarily because Israel says so. When Iraq started getting in to the nuclear weapons program, Israeli warplanes bombed their nuclear reactor to hell. Any serious attemp to develop nukes there will just mean another Israeli strike.<br /><br />And, on another level, BECAUSE WE SAY SO. If the US could have its way, no nations on earth would have large nuclear stockpiles. During the cold war the US supported countries in Europe and India in to developing nukes as a further check against the USSRs then staggering nuclear stockpile (I think at the height of it, the us had 6,000 nukes and the USSR had some 12,000<br />). The US has proven time and time again, that we are willing to cut our nuclear stockpiles if other countries do so with us, and this has occurred to some degree. However, the problem is, now that countries like North Korea and possibly Iraq are planning on developing Nuclear weapons, the whole disarmament process is thrown in to disarray. The US doesn't need nukes to achieve it's foreign policy goals, Iraq however would need nukes to have become the power it wanted to be in the area. Zrazzt, all you are arguing for is nuclear proliferation, so, if you want another cold war, smile and continue as you are.<br /><br />Now, the other HUGE factor is. Iraq lost a war. They invaded a country, they were driven back and signed a cease-fire to stop our attack. In exchange they promised to no longer develop nuclear weapons (among other types). That is the legal reason Iraq will not be permitted to have nukes, that is the requirement of the Iraqi cease-fire after the persian gulf war. <br /><br />Israel is a democratic country. They are indeed involved in very nasty relations with the Palestinians. The Palestinians near the formation of Israel came very close to having peace. Israel however, was invaded by 7 or so Arab powers, and in response Israel took over Jerusalem and other areas in the region. They made the argument that since the arab world was proving itself hostile, they would have to occupy the regions in order to insure their domestic integrity. That is an argument you can agree/disagree with as much as you want, either way it is a sticky situation. Israel's discontents are a small minority of the population. Israel isn't subjugating much of ANYONE inside the borders of Israel. It is the land that Israel is "technically" illegally occupying that causes the problems. Honestly you can't point the finger at Israel decisively. You ought to point it at great britain. Great Britain made promises to several countries in the region concerning the Palestine area. These promises contradicted each other, and when Britain in the end went with its promise to Israel over the others, it caused huge problems. People argue that Israel is illegally occupying parts of Palestine, however, Israel never occupied any land until it was attacked by the Arab nations in retaliation for the Brits duplicity.<br /><br />And, uh, what about India? India isn't a society where anyone who opposes the government is oppressed. India has had and will have for some time a very hard time with it's population. India has around or maybe more than 1 billion people now. This country is extremely diverse and this country does not have a long history of stable national government on its own. The last thing we need to do is start a problem over there which would destabilize the entire country. <br /><br />Now, how does this differ from Iraq? Because in Iraq, the government itself and the leader itself is the cause of the problem. The Iraqi people want liberation. If you don't believe me explain why 14 of the 18 Iraqi provinces were out of Saddams control and in the hands of anti-Saddam rebels during the end of the gulf war? You can't, because the only way to explain that is the people didn't want saddam in power anymore. However when we gave the okay for Iraqis to use attack helicopters on them, we (the international community) insured Saddam staying in power, that was a mistake, just because we made the mistake doesn't mean we should perpetuate it eternally.<br /><br />And uh, on point 3. The United States never signed the treaty of versailles. It signed a separate peace treaty that was basically a simple "cessation of hostilities" with the German nation. So, the prohibitions against German development of an Air Force, the limitations on its Navy and Army, were all agreements of Versailles. It was up to the nations that signed the treaty of Versailles to enforce the prohibitions in the treaty. These nations (France and the United Kingdom primarily) failed to do so. They allowed Hitler to occupy areas of Germany with his army that they he was not, they allowed Hitler to build his Army, Navy, and Air Force in excess of the prohibitions of the treaty. At the time, the isolationist US had no obligations to stop this, for we had not signed the treaty of Versailles which imposed the limits on German military development. It was also France and the United Kingdom that allowed Hitler to seize Austria and Czechoslovakia without so much as a single drop of German blood lost. The fact that Britian and France did nothing then, and the results of their inaction, which includes 100m soldiers and civilians dead, along with 10m jews, gypsies, and soviet citizens killed in the holocaust; simply stress the point that we do not need to wait while provedly aggressive nations rebuild their military against the agreements of a peace treaty.<br /><br />And uh, btw, the "supposedly" can be taken away now. SCUD missiles have been used, those are weapons that Iraq was not allowed to possess. The Kuwaiti army, the British army, the United States Army and from what I understand several "less biased" sources have indeed confirmed that 1-3 of the missiles used against the bases in Kuwait were indeed SCUD missiles. (Again, not 100% sure on this).<br /><br />Rhadamanthus<br />Xegony</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
