                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Drexyll I've learned in the past arguing with you is useless, we will simply never see eye to eye, but I'm bored so here goes.<br /><br />1. YES Israel IS a democracy. The Jews of Israel have many democratic freedoms and live in a fairly democratic society. A minority group in Israel, the Palestinians, do not truly share in these rights. This is much like the system in the U.S. South from then end of reconstruction to about 1964, blacks officially had the right to vote, but in actuality in some states like Mississippi no single black person had registered to vote for over 80 years.<br /><br />Within the borders of Israel democracy IS fairly secure. It is areas like Jerusalem (which is supposed to be more or less an independent city, which Israel seized in 1967 I believe) and the parts of palestine that were set aside for Palestinians that have now been occupied by Israel where a more iron-fisted government style prevails.<br /><br />The simple fact is, Israel was invaded by the entire Arab world. As a response Israel seized Palestinian lands, for it's own protection. Sure, the U.N. doesn't agree, but the fact of the matter is Israel legitimately has concerns over it's territorial integrity. Israel has determined that to protect itself it needed to seize the lands in contention. If you look at the 1948 "official" map of how Israel/Palestine is supposed to be arranged, you will see that Northern and Southern Israel are connected by an extremely thin band of territory forming sort of an "isthmus" between the West bank and the Gaza area I believe, which would make the country fairly indefensible. Nonetheless Israel followed these territorial guidelines until the Arab world launched an invasion against the state of Israel.<br /><br />Facts:<br /><br />1. Israel was formed by the British.<br /><br />2. The British gave Israel land that was promised to the Palestinians AND the Israelis concurrently.<br /><br />3. The fact that the Brits kept their promise to Israel and not Palestine are the source of most of these problems.<br /><br />4. Israel did indeed respect the boundries set by Britain in 148, up until several Arab nations invaded Israel.<br /><br />5. Israel is currently occupying territory for it's national protection.<br /><br />6. Israel has politically repressed Palestinians in occupied territory.<br /><br />7. Palestinian leaders have traditionally argued a more militant response to Israel than a diplomatic response.<br /><br />8. Israel has brutally supressed Palestinians dissidents, comitting some 30-40 massacres of Palestinians since 1948 I believe.<br /><br />Now, those are the facts. My opinion is, if Israel were to follow the U.N. resolutions in question, Israel would be in severe risk of falling to aggressive Arab nations, until Israel is confident the Arab world won't be attacking, this is going to continue to be the case.<br /><br />What is the difference between the U.N. resolutions concerning Israel and the U.N. resolutions concerning Iraq?<br /><br />1. Iraq LOST an aggressive war and agreed to a settlement in which it was required to disarm.<br /><br />2. Israel WON a defensive war and seized territory of its enemies.<br /><br />3. Iraq agreed to disarm and to withdraw from Kuwait.<br /><br />4. Israel agreed to withdraw from some of its conquered territory (Sinai being a good example) but has not agreed to give up wholesale the territory it seized in DEFENSIVE warfare.<br /><br />The prime difference is, Iraq proved to be an AGGRESSIVE nation. Israel proved to be a nation that did not seize land until seriously threatened by the Arab world, an Arab world that has relentlessly lead attacks against Israel.<br /><br />Other facts:<br /><br />1. The Arab world has many many impoverished people.<br /><br />2. Impoverished and destitute people typically look to scapegoats to blame their problems on<br /><br />    -Southern Whites blame blacks(1865-1964+)<br />    -Germans blame the Jews (1920-1945)<br />    -Communists blame "Capitalist Pigs"(1917+)<br /><br />3. The Arab world sees Israel as its scapegoat. They honestly believe their horrible condition is because of Israel. This is not true, their horrible condition is because they are an exploited, underpaid, underfed people who in large part are given just enough from their government to keep them from going in to active rebellion.<br /><br />Rhadamanthus<br />Xegony</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
